06534nam a22007695i 9780824885731DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20202021hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020945492  a97808248857317 a10.1515/97808248857312doi  a(DE-B1597)541898  a(OCoLC)1202470258  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aML410.N594 7aMUS0150002bisacsh04a780.92223/eng1 aHoward, Joshua H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aComposing for the Revolution :bNie Er and China's Sonic Nationalism /cJoshua H. Howard; ed. by Frederick Lau. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2021  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b28 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMusic and Performing Arts of Asia and the Pacific00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIllustrations -- tMusical Examples -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 1 Growing Up in Yunnan: Emergence of a Radical Nationalist -- tCHAPTER 2 Reading Nie Er's Diary: "I Could Be a Symbol for China" -- tCHAPTER 3 The Politics of Music: Ideological Debates and Popularization -- tCHAPTER 4 Composing for the Revolution -- tCHAPTER 5 The Making of a National Icon: Commemorating Nie Er, 1935-1949 -- tCHAPTER 6 Creating the "People's Musician": Socialist Construction and the Film Nie Er -- tCHAPTER 7 Marketing Nie Er in Yunnan: From the "People's Musician" to "Number One Brand" -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Composing for the Revolution: Nie Er and China's Sonic Nationalism, Joshua Howard explores the role the songwriter Nie Er played in the 1930s proletarian arts movement and the process by which he became a nationalist icon. Composed only months before his untimely death in 1935, Nie Er's last song, the "March of the Volunteers," captured the rising anti-Japanese sentiment and was selected as China's national anthem with the establishment of the People's Republic. Nie was quickly canonized after his death and later recast into the "People's Musician" during the 1950s, effectively becoming a national monument. Howard engages two historical paradigms that have dominated the study of twentiethcentury China-revolution and modernity. He argues that active in the leftist artistic community and critical of capitalism, Nie Er availed himself of media technology, especially the emerging sound cinema, to create a modern, revolutionary, and nationalist music. This thesis stands as a powerful corrective to a growing literature on the construction of a Chinese modernity, which has privileged the mass consumer culture of Shanghai and consciously sought to displace the focus on China's revolutionary experience. Composing for the Revolution also provides insight into understudied aspects of China's nationalism-its sonic and musical dimensions. Howard's analyses highlights Nie's extensive writings on the political function of music, examination of the musical techniques and lyrics of compositions within the context of left-wing cinema, and also the transmission of his songs through film, social movements, and commemoration. Nie Er shared multiple and overlapping identities based on regionalism, nationalism, and left-wing internationalism. His march songs, inspired by Soviet "mass songs," combined Western musical structure and aesthetic with elements of Chinese folk music. The songs' ideological message promoted class nationalism, but his "March of the Volunteers" elevated his music to a universal status thereby transcending the nation.Traversing the life and legacy of Nie Er, Howard offers readers a profound insight into the meanings of nationalism and memory in contemporary China. Composing for the Revolution underscores the value of careful reading of sources and the author's willingness to approach a subject from multiple perspectives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aMUSIC / Ethnomusicology.2bisacsh1 aLau, Frederick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2z978311074335708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073968840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780824885731zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824885731423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824885731/original  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070474-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-073968-8  University of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-074335-7  DG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2b2021  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-DKUb2020